<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0006</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Office of the Children’s Rights Director</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:17pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence to the Education Select Committee Inquiry into the Government’s proposals with regard to residential children’s homes </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submitted by Roger Morgan, Children’s Rights Director for England</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children’s views on government proposals for children’s homes, safeguarding and in relation to running away are summarised.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children supported the government proposals to increase responsibility for children’s homes to keep children safe, to include keeping the child safe in every statutory review, to establish checks on safety of the location of children’s homes both generally and on making placements out of home area, for independent monitoring visitors to homes, to check placement suitability for individual children with the local authority before placing out of area, to include prevention of running away in homes’ policies, to review the care plan of a child who frequently runs away, for the police to carry out a safe and well interview with each child who is found after running away and for each child returning from running away from a children’s home to have an interview with an independent person.  On balance, children supported the Director of Children’s Services having to agree any care plan for a child to leave care at 16 or 17.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children favour a definition of a distant placement as one that is more than two hours’ travelling time away.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children were concerned that the final decision on distant placement should not be made by the Director of Children’s Services, but by a panel of those who know the child.  It is therefore recommended that the relevant Regulations be amended to clarify the role of the Director of Children’s Services in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">decisionmaking</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on distant placement is one of being satisfied that the decision has been properly made by those who know the child in accordance with the child’s safety and needs.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most frequent reasons for distant placement were to remove the child from trouble and risks in their home area and to prevent running back to the family home they had been removed from.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children in distant placements considered (by 49% to 6%) that distant placement made them safer rather than less safe.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A summary of children’s views relevant to safeguarding in children’s homes, and to running away from placements, is set out for the Committee’s reference.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I am submitting this document as a summary of children’s views, in my capacity as Children’s Rights Director, with a statutory duty to ascertain the views of children within my remit, which includes children in children’s homes.  My aim is to provide an independently summarised account of the views of children themselves, without adding additional material or my own views or comments.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The children’s views on the current Government proposals come from a children’s consultation survey just completed, which will be the subject of a full report to be published in October of this year.  Key points listed at the end of this submission are from previously published children’s views reports.  I am not speaking on behalf of any organisation, and do not speak on behalf of Ofsted, the body which currently hosts my Office.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The recent consultation survey sought children’s views on each of 12 proposals from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> consultation documents issued on 23 April 2013.  The wording of the questions was checked with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.  Invitations for children to participate in a secure web survey were sent to all children’s homes in England.  594 children responded to the survey.  Their median age was 15.  60% were boys and 40% girls.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Other than being asked whether they voted FOR, AGAINST or DON’T KNOW on each government proposal, the children were not given any suggested answers to questions asking them for their reasons for the way they voted.  Reasons given in this submission are therefore categorised from their own free text answers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Findings from the consultation survey </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The majority of children responding to the consultation survey supported all but two of the government proposals we listed from the relevant consultation documents.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Well over half of the children responding voted FOR each of the following ten government proposals (listed in descending order of support given, with the percentage of children voting who voted in favour of each proposal):</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:466.1pt"><tr style="height:23.05pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Every Review of every child’s care plan must (as well as lots of other things) check wheth</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">er the child is being kept safe (82% in favour).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The law already says that the person running a children’s home must look after the children properly. In future it should also say they are responsible for keeping the children safe, and that the plan for each child in the home must say how that child is to be kept safe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (77% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.05pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In future, the person running a children’s home must check if the area is safe for the children to live in. They should deal with any risks there are - and should by law check this out every year with the police and children’s social care services</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (72% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Before a council places a child away from their home area, it must talk to the council for the new area first about whether the home is in a safe or risky area for the child to move into</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (71% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The law already says that every children’s home must have a policy that says what will happen if someone runs away. As well as this, in future the policy should say what the home will do, with the police and other people, to PREVENT children from running away</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (70% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Whenever someone who has run away returns to the home, the police should talk with them about where they have been, anything that has happened while they were away, and whether they are safe and well</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (67% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The person running a children’s home should ask social care services for a Review of a child’s care plan if the child keeps running away from the home</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (66% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Before a council places a child away from their home area, it must talk to the council for the new area first, and send them the child’s care plan, to help decide whether it will be the right placement for the child</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (65% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The people running each children’s home should choose a really independent person to visit the home every month to check that it is being run properly (and the independent person should usually not tell the staff when they are coming to visit)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (61% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Whenever someone has run away, they should have the chance to talk to somebody who is independent of the home before they come back to the home – about why they ran away, whether they feel safe at the home, whether they need any extra help at the home, and about anything that happened to them while they were away</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (61% in favour)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The following proposal was supported, but by fewer than half the children voting:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To stop young people being made to leave care before they are ready, if someone’s plan says they will be leaving care at 16 or 17 (instead of 18), then their whole care plan would have to be agreed by the Director of Children’s Services (44% in favour).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The one proposal opposed by the children voting was:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Director of Children’s Services should be the only person who can decide to place a child a long way from their home area (45% against, 25% in favour, 30% undecided, 565 children voted).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The top five reasons given by children for opposing this proposal were:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:29.1pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The decision should be made by more than one person (from 24% of those against the proposal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Director of Children’s Services doesn’t know the child (from 19% of those against the proposal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child should be more involved (from 16% of those against the proposal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Parents or family should be more involved (from 15% of those against the proposal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The decision should be made by the child’s social worker (from 14% of those against the proposal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The most frequent reason for children’s opposition to the proposal, that the decision should be made by more than one person, was based on two main grounds.  Firstly, that in principle such an important decision for a child should not be in the hands of one person, but should be made by a panel or a group of people sharing their views about what is best for the child.  As two children put it, the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">decisionmaker</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> ‘shouldn’t be one person’, ‘should be a group decision’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Secondly, many children wished the decision to involve people who most directly knew the child and what was best for the child, such as their social worker, current carers, and (where appropriate) parents.  To quote one child, ‘it should be decided by a group of adults that have worked with the child, so that they can come up with the best thing for the child’.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The next most frequent reason for children opposing this proposal was related to this.  It was that the Director of Children’s Services is someone who does not know the child, and children were generally clear that such a key decision should be made for the child by people who know the child well enough to make the right decision for that individual child.  As one child put this, ‘the Director only knows what he has read on paper and hasn’t actually met the young person’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The children’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">responses</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">do not support the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">final </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">decisionmaker</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on placement a long way awa</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">y from the home area being </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the Director of Children’s Services</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – and they </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">present the alternative of such decisions being made by a panel of people with direct knowledge of the child and their needs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">It appears important to children that the role of the Director in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">distant placement should not be that of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> final </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">or sole </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">decisionmaker</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and the decision itself should be taken by a group who personally know the child and their needs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Distance versus travel time in defining a whether a placement is a long way away</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:4.8pt"><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:451.95pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Out of 586 children responding to the question, 57% told us that they were placed away from their home area.  The question asked them whether they defined their placement as away from their home area, therefore for some children a placement in a different town in a large local authority may be defined by the child as out of their home area even though it may be in the same local authority area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:14.15pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:68.3pt"><td colspan="2" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:466.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We asked children to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">define whether distance or travel time was the major factor in d</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">efining </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">whether</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a placement feel</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a long way away from their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">home area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.  Out of 567 children responding, half (50%) said that the main factor was the time it took to get there, with only 25% saying that it was the distance there in miles.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The median definition of what </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">children </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">felt to be a long time to travel </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">between their home area and a placement </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">was two hours.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><!--[if !supportMisalignedColumns]><tr style="height:0pt"><td style="width:451.95pt; border:none"></td><td style="width:14.15pt; border:none"></td></tr><![endif]--></table><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reasons for placement away from home area</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We asked children to tell us the reasons for their placement away from their home area.  308 children responded to this question.  Of these, 64 (53%) said they didn’t know the reason for their placement away from their home area.  229 children gave reasons.  The most frequent reasons given were:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Needed to be placed away from the area for the child’s own safety (from 18% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The more distant placement was chosen to meet the child’s needs (from 14% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Because the child had previously absconded home from closer placements (from 12% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child needed to be kept away from contact with their parents or family (from 10% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">There was no closer placement available (from 10% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child needed to be placed away to keep them from getting into trouble in their own area (from 9% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Because of the child’s behaviour in a previous placement (from 4% of those who gave reasons).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In summary, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">over half the children did not know why they had been placed away from their home area, but those who did told us that they had been placed away from the area in order to meet their needs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.  These included a distant placement being needed for their own safety and protection, meeting their needs better than other placements, being chosen because of a history of absconding back home from closer placements, and the need to keep them away from their families or to keep them away from trouble they were involved in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> their home area.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Only one in ten children told us they had been placed away from their home area because of a lack of local placements</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> In some of those cases, the child qualified their response by saying that the distant placement was still the nearest that was available (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> ‘they couldn’t find anywhere closer’, ‘it was the closest home they could get me in’).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Effects of placement away from home on safety</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">We asked children who were placed away from their home area whether they thought this had made a difference to their safety.  322 answered this question, out of the 332 who told us they were placed away from their home area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overall, the children’s view was that being placed out of area was </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">much </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">more likely to make you safer than less safe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Almost half the children, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">49%, told us that being placed away from their home area had made them safer, while only 6% told us that it had made them less safe.  45% of those placed away from their home area thought this had made no difference</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> at all to their safety.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">From those who thought they were now safer because they had been placed out of their home area, the main reasons given by the 156 who responded to this question were:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Good care and support at the placement (from 29% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child is away from what was getting them into trouble in their home area (from 26% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child is well away from risks from their family (from 13% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child is away from threats to their safety in their home area (from 11% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The child is no longer absconding back to the family home they were removed from (from 11% of those who gave reasons)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Direct quotations illustrating some of these responses are; ‘I don’t  have the people to lead me into doing silly things – the staff have helped me to learn how to keep myself safe’, ‘I’m no longer encouraged to hang with the wrong people and get myself into trouble’, ‘not being with troublemakers and not becoming involved in trouble’, ‘it’s safer because I’m not near my mum’, ‘I can no longer put myself at risk or in dangerous situations’, ‘I couldn’t run off to my mum and dad’s’.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">One child summed up the mixed feelings of being safer away from risks at home, but also feeling isolated from home; ‘in some ways it makes me feel safer because I know that my family can’t come and find me – but then in another way I wish I was still near them’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">These findings are corroborated by an in depth focus group discussion we had previously held on the subject of out of authority placements.  That group advised that the key factors in deciding to place a child at a distance were to keep them away from trouble in their home area, and a history of absconding home when placed close to home.  That focus group also reported very variable levels of contact with social workers and Independent Reviewing Officers once placed at a distance – varying from continued close contact and good relationships to loss of contact and of working relationships.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Sixteen children in our survey gave reasons for being placed at home making them feel less safe than they had been in their home area.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Seven of these said that they felt less safe with unfamiliar people in an unfamiliar place</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, and four said they missed their old friends and family nearer home.  Two said their new area was no less ‘rough’ than their home area, two told us they were still absconding back home which they knew was not a safe thing for them to do, and one said that they were now away from the protection members of their family had given them against other people in their home area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key safeguarding points from</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">children’s assessment of social care in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">(The Children’s Care Monitor 2011, Office of the Children’s Rights Director)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The Committee may find it useful to know the key points from the most recently published Monitor.  Of children living in children’s homes:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">90% felt very or fairly safe in the building where they lived (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">compared</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> with 94% of children in care or living away from home overall)</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">87% felt very or fairly safe at school or college</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">79% felt very or fairly safe when out in the countryside</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">78% felt very or fairly safe in towns or cities (compared with 73% of children in care or living away from home overall)</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children living in children’s homes reported the two factors most likely to make them feel safer were being with adults they trust and having more  police or security people around  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children living in children’s homes reported the top five dangers to children of their own age (in descending order of frequency) as drugs, alcohol, bullying, knives, and strangers among the public </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">43% of children living in children’s homes identified strangers as a major danger to themselves, compared with 48% of children across all settings</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">24% said there was nothing that would make them safer than they are now</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">36% reported worrying a little or a lot about their safety</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The five top people children living in children’s homes would go to for help if they felt unsafe were, in descending order of frequency;  staff of their children’s home (84%), a social worker (64%), the police (59%), a friend (55%), a parent (48%).</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key safeguarding points regarding safeguarding in children’s homes from other consultations by the Office of the Children’s Rights Director</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I hope the Committee will find it useful to have a ready reference list of the key points made by children that are relevant to safeguarding, children’s homes and children going missing from care.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The key messages below are summarised from our independent statutory consultations to ascertain the views of children and young people in care</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Out of a list of 36 children’s rights, children from care settings or living away from home in residential education voted the top children’s right of all as being protected from abuse</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The top protection in safeguarding children is listening well to each child, taking their concerns seriously and taking action if needed</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Staff need to be good at hearing the quiet children, not only those who are good at making their views known</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Professionals need to be good at keeping confidentiality and good at identifying – and telling the child – when they need to pass something on for their safety.  Many children do not tell professionals private things if they fear they will become too widely known</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Many children will not tell highly personal information, or information about ‘rude things’, to professionals – like some social workers - who they do not already know well and trust and who they find scary </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Teenagers are at risk of harm, as well as younger children, and boys as well as girls</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The internet is a major and growing means of grooming of children and young people</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Bullying is the top fear of harm</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> from others</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Abuse and bullying are well countered in secure children’s homes, but many in secure units fear leaving and becoming again exposed to the risks to them among the general public and from peer groups they used to belong to before entering secure residential care</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The greatest risk of abuse is on the streets</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Care leavers often feel unsafe in the locations they are placed to live alone after leaving the safety and support of care</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children feel more vulnerable and less safe from abuse when they are newly placed with people they don’t yet know and trust</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">You need to assess what and where is risky, but you cannot ever make everything safe and you need to keep a balance between enabling people to live a normal life and protecting people</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children want regular and frequent inspections of children’s homes</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Staff of a children’s home are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the key factor in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">keeping children of the home safe</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children in children’s homes need to know which members of staff are the ones they should go to if they have fears about abuse</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children in children’s homes have identified the top four factors keeping them safe </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">at the home </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">as:  staff, building safety, talking with staff or </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">keyworkers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> about issues and concerns, and the rules set in the home</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In one of our surveys, just over half the children responding told us that adults sometimes gave them conflicting advice on how they should keep themselves safe</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is important for even very young children to be told very frankly what the risks and nature of abuse are – even if telling them scares them</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">A child or young person is very likely to confide concerns about their personal safety, or concerns about abuse, to a friend before an adult or professional.  It is important that children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">know about the child protection system and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">are taught what to do if a friend tells them they are being abused</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is essential that children have the opportunity regularly to speak to their social worker alone about their care and any concerns, without others present or able to hear</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children running away from care settings are at risk of both getting involved in crime, and of being sexually exploited.  Those in care settings sometimes know of children who have run away and disappeared completely</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">There are four main reasons for running away from care settings:  running simply to have fun before coming back, running to somewhere the child want</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">stay</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> or someone they want to be with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> (such as going back to their family)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, running away from something they can’t cope with where they are living, and finally being counted as having run away when </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">like many teenagers </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">you are simply overdue home or have been where you didn’t have permission to be</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Some children have told us they have run away from care settings because they could not get something sorted out through raising them with staff or through complaints procedures</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">The three main ways of reducing the rate of children running away are:  listening properly and seriously to children’s concerns</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> about their lives or placements</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, taking action to sort concerns or complaints rapidly and not dismissing or delaying</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">, and if and when children return from running, asking them their reasons for running and sorting out any concerns that led the child to run away</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Returning a child who has run away straight back to where they ran from is not a good practice – they need to be offered the opportunity to speak to someone independent they trust and to be listened to seriously in deciding whether it is safe to return them to somewhere they ran from</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Children are less likely to run from care settings which:  have good staff, organise plenty of activities, counter bullying, listen well to children, are good at helping with problems children tell them about</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Based on the views, concerns and advice of children set out in this submission:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">That the Committee urge the Government to take the views expressed by children on safeguarding, children’s homes, running away, and amendments to planning, placement and review Regulations, fully into account in the final changes finally made.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">That the definition of distance in placement be based on travel time of over two hours.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.18pt; padding-left:2.82pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">That in line with the children’s sensitivity expressed on this issue, the role of the Director of Children’s Services in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">decisionmaking</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> on distant placement be more clearly defined in the final Regulations as one of checking that the decision made by those who know the child and their needs (</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> in a statutory review) has been properly reached and accords with the child’s needs and safety, including any needs to be placed away from trouble or risks in the child’s home area – effectively one of ratification of process rather than of involvement in making the decision itself.  To this end I suggest the following revised wording of Regulation 3 (a) (1) (b) of the Draft Amendment Regulations: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">“in the case of a proposed placement which is also at a distance, must not be put into effect until the Director of Children’s Services personally is satisfied that the decision has been properly reached under these Regulations, is in the best interests of the safety and welfare of the child, and will meet the child’s needs.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Safe from harm (2004)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Children’s views on restraint (2004)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Children’s views on standards (2006)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">About social workers (2006)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Running away (2006)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Children and safeguarding (2007)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Life in children’s homes (2009)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Life in secure care (2009)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Children on rights and responsibilities (2010)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Getting advice (2010)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Younger children’s views (2011)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Children’s experiences of child protection procedures (2012)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, Running away (2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>